  "prompt": "What is act exam?",
  "response": "The ACT (American College Testing) is a standardized college admissions exam used primarily in the United States. Here are key details about the ACT:\n\n1. Purpose\n- Measures academic readiness for college\n- Used by colleges and universities for admissions decisions\n- Helps colleges compare applicants from different high schools\n\n2. Test Sections\n- English\n- Mathematics\n- Reading\n- Science\n- Optional Writing section\n\n3. Scoring\n- Each section is scored from 1-36\n- Composite score is the average of the four main sections\n- Total possible score is 36\n\n4. Test Administration\n- Typically taken by high school juniors and seniors\n- Offered multiple times per year (usually 6-7 times)\n- Computer-based and paper-based options\n- Duration: About 3 hours (with optional writing section)\n\n5. Test Preparation\n- Many students take preparatory courses\n- Practice tests are available\n- Can be retaken to improve scores\n\n6. Acceptance\n- Most colleges and universities in the U.S. accept ACT scores\n- Often used alongside or instead of the SAT\n\nThe ACT is designed to assess a student's general educational development and ability to complete college-level work.",
